  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous statutes that address money laundering at both the national and international levels. Here are some key examples:\n\n### United States\n1. **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970**: This act requires financial institutions to assist government agencies in detecting and preventing money laundering by maintaining certain records and reporting suspicious activities.\n2. **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**: This act made money laundering a federal crime, establishing specific offenses and penalties for those involved in money laundering activities.\n3. **USA PATRIOT Act of 2001**: This act expanded the scope of the BSA and introduced additional measures to prevent, detect, and prosecute money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n### European Union\n1. **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)**: The EU has issued several directives, such as the 4th AMLD (2015) and 5th AMLD (2018), which set out requirements for member states to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n2. **Regulation (EU) 2018/1672**: This regulation establishes measures to prevent money laundering and terrorist financing, particularly in relation to the use of cash and prepaid cards.\n\n### International\n1. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations**: The FATF is an intergovernmental organization that sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Its recommendations are widely adopted by countries around the world.\n2. **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**: Also known as the Vienna Convention, it includes provisions for combating money laundering related to drug trafficking.\n3. **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**: Also known as the Palermo Convention, it includes provisions for combating money laundering related to organized crime.\n\n### Other Countries\n1. **United Kingdom**: The Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 (POCA) is a key piece of legislation that addresses money laundering.\n2. **Canada**: The Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act (PCMLTFA) is the primary law addressing money laundering.\n3. **Australia**: The Anti-Money Laundering and Counter-Terrorism Financing Act 2006 (AML/CTF Act) is the main legislation.\n\nThese statutes and regulations generally require financial institutions to implement robust anti-money laundering (AML) programs, conduct customer due diligence (CDD), maintain records, and report suspicious transactions to relevant authorities. Penalties for non-compliance can be severe, including hefty fines and imprisonment.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
